node.text:
“It makes sense that every aspect of a deVOL Kitchen, right down to the handles, should be equally well designed and made. Good design is all about equal consideration for every aspect, form, aesthetic, utility etc. The quality of deVOL is in their attention to detail, the last finishing touches.” - Stephanie O'Leary, deVOL's jeweller and metalsmith. 
#deVOLKitchens

node.title: How we make deVOL handcrafted kitchen handles...

node.text: We did an Instagram story a few months ago now, it was a little behind the scenes look into the @devolceramics studio and a brand new product that we were experimenting with and developing. We always show you the finished products but there's talented people working and being inventive and creative every single day at our Cotes Mill studios, so we love to try and show you as much of the making process as possible. We did a little vote in the story and nearly all of you said you'd like to see these tiles be added as a permanent product to our tile range... so here's a little update! They're not totally ready yet but Hannah is almost there... using our new (but very old!!) tile press and imprinting some of her grandma's vintage lace, she has created the loveliest glossy, Victorian inspired tiles in rich shades of burgundy and blue and pink and brown. As soon as the final tiles are complete and colours and shapes are chosen and they're up on the website we'll let you know, but for now, we hope you enjoy this video of Hannah in action! #deVOLKitchens

node.title: In The Studio: making vintage lace tiles

node.text: Have a little look around @pearllowe's fairytale home and one of our most-loved kitchens ever!! This is eclectic English eccentricity at its very best. A little bit romantic, a little bit edgy and totally unique - we love Pearl's style and feel very lucky to have been able to work with her on this dream of a kitchen. What's your favourite part? #deVOLKitchens

node.text: A little look inside the beautiful Millhouse showrooms with original music, written and performed by Stuart DeRouen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by deVOL Kitchens in Germany with @_foodstories_, and @_designtales_. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
The mix of materials and colours is what really makes this kitchen and all Laura and Nora’s renovations so memorable, they have an ease of style and tend to create rooms that have a simplicity and natural feel, yet they infuse them with a little glam. We take so much inspiration from these two and are truly grateful for the way they have embraced deVOL and all our accessories in such a confident and clever way, and allowed us to share their beautiful photographs with you. #deVOLKitchens

Lovely photo and styling by Laura and Nora of @_foodstories_ / @_designtales_

node.text: For a truly authentic English kitchen, a simple cream or off white for your cupboards is good and very easy to live with but for real drama and tradition, we would suggest darker colours, muted navys, deep reds, murky yellows and dense greens. The key is to get a dullness to the colour so it doesn't shout bold or brash, but warm and rich and soft. Going for matte colours is also an easy way to achieve an instantly more lived-in look and feel. Our paints are matte with just a teeny touch of sheen to ensure the surfaces don't look totally flat and you can just pick up the hand-painted brush strokes when they catch the light. #deVOLKitchens

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by deVOL Kitchens in Cardiff, Wales, United Kingdom with @a_prettier_interior. May be an image of indoor.

node.text: Leonard Koren famously said ‘pare down the essence, but don’t remove the poetry’, and we think that’s exactly what the owners did here. They carried out a renovation that didn’t really feel like a renovation at all, more of a restoration. They hunted down reclaimed doors and floors, all with that beautiful sense of poetry, but avoided anything too fussy or over the top. Instead, they chose just a few of our hand-painted Shaker cupboards and some simple aged brass hardware. It’s one of those kitchens that so naturally weaves itself into the fabric of the house and feels like it could have been sitting there for years and years… #deVOLKitchens

node.text: There is something rather special about a sink and a window. Gazing out, lost in thoughts while peeling the potatoes or arranging some flowers. All made even better by a sink as beautiful as this one. 800mm wide, double bowled and fluted at the front for a little extra detail. They are a bit more expensive than the plain Belfast sinks, but sometimes it's these small design choices that end up being the best decisions you make. We can usually recommend ways to save a little money somewhere else if you have your heart set on something special. Splurging and saving can help you keep your budget in check and allow you to get what you really want. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: Crittall-style doors and windows make this room feel almost as if it is outside, and mixed with the exposed Bath stone walls that are so rustic, old and natural, the contrast is very cleverly done. Looking at the bones of a space is always where the design should begin and finding natural texture is the best and luckiest of starts for any room. It had to be our Sebastian Cox range of cupboards here, sustainable and tactile and easygoing, they look good pretty much anywhere but with a backdrop like this, the outcome is magic. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: Happy Friday everyone! We thought we'd share one of our favourites this evening. Did anyone spot this in the first episode of For the Love of Kitchens? It's a place you really have to see to believe, a moated medieval house with wrought iron gates and fallow deer and acres of parkland. You can just see a little hint of the impressive grounds and fabulous arched windows reflected in these glazed doors. We love seeing these old favourites brought to life on film and you get to meet the lovely owner @the.history.keeper too, what a treat. #deVOLKitchens

node.text: Honed or polished marble? It's a question that always comes up in our design appointments and here on our Instagram. There's no right or wrong but understanding the differences will make decision making easier. Aesthetically, polished is more luxe and glamorous, and honed is more understated. In terms of durability, polishing the surface of your marble adds a layer of protection, so for things like red wine spills, the substance is less likely to completely penetrate and stain the surface if it’s polished compared to honed. A honed finish is slightly better at hiding scratches, but these will still be visible no matter the finish you choose. With acidic substances like lemon juice or vinegar, a honed finish will hold up better. If you spill lemon juice on a polished marble it will cause etchings and ultimately take away the shiny effect, leaving a slightly matt patch. We tend to go for a honed finish more often than not but sometimes a space just calls for a little extra glamour and nothing but polished will do! #deVOLKitchens
